es:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ballon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Sergio, Alfonso, Cesar, Conchita, Emigdio, Enrique, Felipe, Francisco, Jose Luis, Julio, Ruben.  Jewish Hyman, Isadore.","Spanish and Galician: unexplained.","French and English (Middlesex): from the Old French personal name <i>Ballon</i>, <i>Ballun</i>, derived from the oblique stem of ancient Germanic <i>Ballo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’ (see   Ballard  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ballard","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>ballard</i> ‘bald-headed man’ (compare   Bald   3).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Balhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’, and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Ballor  ."]},{"name":"Ballam","meanings":["English (Dorset): variant of <b>Balaam</b> (assimilated by folk etymology to the Biblical personal name <i>Balaam</i>, see Numbers 23–24), which is a habitational name from Baylham in Suffolk or a Norman surname derived from Ballon in Le Mans, Sarthe, France (compare   Ballon  ). The surname may also be a variant of English <b>Balham</b>, perhaps from Balham in Streatham, Surrey, named with Old English <i>bealg</i> ‘smooth’ or ‘round’ + <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow, land hemme